General FAQ

This document is a community driven full breakdown of the respective class. This is a live document where we actively change it based on feedback and changes to the game to provide the best information to the community. The majority of us hang around in the Community Lost Ark Discord in our respective class channels. If you would like to give us feedback or ask questions contact us there.

Why should I play this class?

In one class you have two drastically different builds to pick from: one is a non-positional, high survivability, and unique transformation build, while the other focuses on your human form, boosting skill damage with your identity gauge.

How does my identity work?

Shadowhunter utilizes a Shadowburst gauge, this gauge is filled by using your skills and the amount of gauge generation is based on the Specialization stat. Demonic Impulse heavily relies on this for entering transformation state, once the gauge is full they can transform, once they de-transform they regenerate a full gauge and repeat. For Perfect Suppression certain skills can utilize the built up gauge for more damage increase since you are unable to utilize the transformation state.

How do I decide on a build?

Both have their strengths and weaknesses. It’s a matter of personal preference.

For further information, read the respective sections of this document.

When does it feel good to play?

Both shadowhunter builds feel mediocre in Tier 1 and Tier 2 due to various shortcomings solved in Tier 3. Demonic impulse requires a minimum specialization to transform in one rotation, which can be met with Epic or Legendary Tier 3 accessories, appropriate wealth runes, and Encroaching Power tripods. As a result, playing Demonic Impulse before 1370 will feel lackluster. As for Perfect Suppression it really starts to pick up once you have your “full kit”, a combination of relic set, gems, and tripods making it feel significantly better to play.

What are the key pieces of my build?

Runes

Demonic Impulse really benefits from Wealth Runes and high Specialization to build gauge with less skills.

Perfect Suppression makes good use of Conviction + Judgment runes to help with mana management and cooldowns.

Skill Points

While skill point potions are nearly useless for Demonic Impulse — since demonic skills aren’t levelable — they help to boost Perfect Supression’s damage a bit further with level 11/12 spenders and hard-hitting skills.

Demonic Impulse

Written by Natt, Shandamon, Sekwah, EigtheenNoodles

Playstyle

Demonic Impulse is a build which revolves entirely around Shadowhunter’s transformed state, Demon Form. This build uses skills designed for maximum gauge gain while in human form to quickly transform. While transformed, it deals consistent damage and has great survivability.

Stat Allocation

This build takes Specialization as its primary stat, since it affects Demon Skill damage, transform duration, and the rate Shadowburst gauge is generated.

Crit or Swiftness can be taken as the secondary stat depending on which engravings and relic set are chosen.

Hallucination is an alternative which when paired with Swiftness as a secondary stat, allows us to make full use of Raid Captain as a 5th engraving.

After your 4 mandatory engravings (Demonic Impulse, Grudge, Keen Blunt Weapon, Adrenaline), you can choose between 3 options for your 5th engraving; Raid Captain, Cursed Doll, or Hit Master.

  • Cursed Doll is a 15.09% damage engraving due to the reduced efficiency from also running Adrenaline 3.
  • Hit Master is around 15.2% damage because it does not affect Awakening, Bleed and some Human skills.
  • Raid Captain is a higher damage engraving than Cursed Doll or Hit Master if you can achieve at least 33.8% movespeed bonus.

For Spec/Swift build, this can be easily achieved with any Swiftness necklace (Legendary or higher) and a Support with Yearning relic set. For Spec/Crit build, there are a few limited ways to achieve this, detailed below.

To achieve at least 33.54% movespeed on a Spec/Crit build, you need to obtain movespeed bonuses from multiple sources. These are the current sources available:

  1. Demonic Impulse transformation (20% movespeed)
  2. Swiftness stats from roster rewards, potions, and card collections (up to 0.96% movespeed)
  3. A Support with Yearning relic set (8-10-12% movespeed)
  4. Feast with that offers movespeed as the RNG bonus stat when crafted (3.50% movespeed)
  5. Vernese Wine from the merchant on Peyto or Cradle of the Sea Fermata islands (3% movespeed)
  6. A bracelet with swiftness stat (up to 1.71% movespeed)
  7. Nimble Movement tripod from Demonic Slash (20% movespeed for 6 seconds, which is only enough for the first few skills inside transformation)

If you can achieve at least 33.8% movespeed with any combination of these sources, then Raid Captain can be taken over Cursed Doll or Hit Master.

Since a Spec/Crit bracelet is a higher damage increase than a Spec/Swift bracelet, and movespeed bonuses from feasts are RNG dependent, the optimal combination of movespeed sources is as follows:

Demonic Impulse transformation (20%) + Swiftness stats from roster rewards, potions, and card collections (0.96%) + Level 2 Yearning (10%) + Vernese Wine (3%) = 33.96% movespeed (15.28% damage from Raid Captain)

FAQ: Demonic Impulse

Questions sourced from frequent interactions within the Unofficial Lost Ark Discord #Shadowhunter
This section is ever-growing, and new FAQ submissions are always welcome.

What relic set is better, Hallucination or Salvation?

Both Hallucination and Salvation are viable for all content in the game. With that said, once the minimum requirements are met Salvation is generally stronger than Hallucination as long as stacks are maintained.

Hallucination with Crit as a Secondary stat is mathematically better than Salvation Crit, but without the Attack Speed and CDR from Swiftness (or just ATK Speed from Salvation) it hardly performs the same in real scenarios.

After we get Elixirs (with Voldis), there’s 2 “Elixir Set” choices you can pick from:

  • Master: Provides up to 7% Crit Rate and 8.5% Additional Damage at level 2
  • Repentance: Provides 12% Damage on Crit (not the same as crit damage) at level 2.

Since all builds run adrenaline in one form or the other, and we have high crit rate due to Demonic Impulse engraving (and/or Crit secondary stat, Hallucination relic set), the ideal choice for us is Repentance.

This elixir benefits you more the higher you go on crit rate, therefore Hallucination+Crit gains a slightly bigger boost than Salvation+Crit does due to the high crit rate. This should translate into more damage in ideal scenarios, but at the cost of QoL (in the form of move speed from Swiftness) or some damage from Attack Speed (from Salvation or Swiftness).

The TL;DR would be:

  • Pick Hallucination Crit if you’re chasing the ceiling (or if you’re failing to keep up Salvation stacks)
  • Pick Salvation for a slightly lower damage ceiling but an increase in comfiness
  • Pick Hallucination Swift if you like to zoom zoom around :D at the cost of damage

I can’t transform in one rotation, what can I do?

If the character’s item level is below 1370, it’s really hard to get enough spec to easily transform in one rotation. At or after 1370, it should be possible to transform in one rotation with proper Tripod levels. Higher quality accessories and runes help aid in transformation.

How much Specialization is enough?

All you can get. Spec is everything for Demonic Impulse. It’s our only true way to scale outside of gems/engravings. It provides damage and transform duration (which means even more damage), allows us to spend less time in Human Form by reducing the amount of skills used to transform and you never have enough of it.

When should I switch to Salvation?

If you want to switch to Salvation, ensure you meet both the Specialization and Demonic Skill cooldown gem requirements. A bracelet with Specialization and a Level 8 Demonic Skill Cooldown Gem is (barely) enough to use Leaping Blow and Blood Massacre three times in one rotation. Before bracelets, a Level 9 Demonic Skill Cooldown Gem is the bare minimum to have a three A/S rotation. However, in both cases a Level 10 Demonic Skill Cooldown Gem is strongly recommended for the rotation to be achievable in a real raid setting.

How important are tripods to this build?

They only matter to the extent of being able to transform in one rotation; if the spec and tripod requirements are met they do not provide value beyond that. The non-gauge generation tripods listed as a lower priority exist solely for quality of life.

Can I run a <x Stat> accessory instead of a Spec accessory?

No. Never. Do not talk to me.

(It's a very big damage loss)

When should/can I start using Spinning Dive instead of Thrust Impact?

As soon as your specialization is sufficient to transform in one rotation, Spinning Dive is okay to take over Thrust Impact. Thrust Impact serves as a back up skill in case you miss too many Intrude Skills.

Entropy Perfect Suppression

Written by Jsim

Playstyle

Perfect Suppression disables the Demonize identity ability in exchange for increased damage from normal skills and increased Shadowburst gauge generation from all skills. This setup offers a higher DPS ceiling than the Demonic Impulse build, but requires a lot more minmaxing on gems, tripods, skill rotation management and back attacking in order to be competitive. The Perfect Suppression build offers a more burst-oriented, fast-paced playstyle while still being highly sustainable in encounters with plenty of DPS downtime (e.g. Legion Raids). Perfect Suppression Shadowhunters build Shadowburst gauge with generation skills to empower certain Normal skills with Encroachment Release tripods, which consumes 20% of the Shadowburst gauge in return for a significant increase in damage output, typically called spender skills. With a correct balance between generation skills and spenders, gauge management is easy and you will be ready to unload your spenders at any opportunity you get.

Stat Allocation

Due to early game mana constraints you will benefit more from crit stat. After you have your relic set, the ideal distribution of Crit and Swiftness varies depending on your engraving choices. See the example engravings section for suggested combinations of engravings and stat distributions.

Perfect Suppression

Written by Sekwah

Playstyle

This build differs from Entropy, removing the requirement of back-attacks and solving mana problems, but performing slightly worse in terms of damage. While it still possesses the characteristics of Perfect Suppression gameplay, it does so with a few new abilities and more comfort which guarantees different enjoyment.

Crit

  • Full Crit has the highest DPC (damage per cycle), but long cooldowns. Recommended with high level (9+) CD gems.
  • Full Swift (4Dom2NM) has the highest DPS (damage per second), but any amount of downtime heavily impacts it. Recommended with high (1800+) Swiftness due to Dominion downtime
  • Full Swift (6 Nightmare) is an alternative to 4Dom2NM, with lower DPS but no need to manage Dominion nor Conviction and Judgment.
  • 60/40 and 50/50 stat splits attempt to help with cooldowns by trading some amount of crit for comfort, allowing for lower level CD gems.

FAQ: Perfect Suppression

Questions sourced from frequent interactions within the Unofficial Lost Ark Discord #Shadowhunter
This section is ever-growing, and new FAQ submissions are always welcome.

Which Relic Set to use?

Choose based on your preferred playstyle.

Entropy is the set used for the back attack centered Perfect Suppression build, maximizing the raw damage output of successful back attacks, which gives this build  the highest potential damage per burst cycle. The raid performance of this build is heavily dependent on the player’s consistency with landing all damage skills as successful back attacks with minimal loss of uptime. Due to relatively long cooldowns, even with full swiftness builds, the playstyle of this build can be described as a short, front-loaded burst style with enough downtime in between cycles to give room for positioning and building up identity gauge.

Nightmare is the recommended set for nonpositional Perfect Suppression builds, which eliminates the need for successful back attacks, allowing a faster paced, more consistent damage dealing playstyle by utilizing Nightmare’s Boundless MP state, without the need to constantly position around landing successful back attacks.

4Dom2NM has shorter cooldowns and is more “spammy” but you need to keep up the buff, and in some fights like Brel G5/G6 it is impossible due to fight length and awakening charges. It also adds a complexity layer to gameplay (having to keep track of Dominion + Reapplying it during Conviction + Judgement windows) which is not recommended for inexperienced players.

How do I deal with mana problems?

There are 2 main ways to increase your mana regeneration and a few supplemental ways. If you are running into mana issues, check how many of the following you have.

Main mana generation sources:

  • Support casting Heavenly Blessing with the Absolute Blessing tripod (Paladin) or Heavenly Tune (Bard)
  • Mana Regeneration food (called Combat Resource natural recovery in game, such as Herb Steak Meals)

Supplementary sources of mana:

  • Having an MP Regeneration line on a bracelet (20% chance to recover 125/150/175 MP per skill cast) or a Max MP line.

  • Partying with a Summoner using the MP Recovery tripod on Shurdi
  • Leveling up if you are not yet level 60

Raid Captain and Keen Blunt Weapon efficiency

Raid Captain is easy to cap if you run Demonic Slash Lv7 tripod, Nimble Movement, since it provides up to 30% movespeed for a few seconds. But if you want to run alternative skill setups where you drop Demonic Slash to 4 (or completely) or don’t like to be tied to a strict rotation, you need at least 1400 Swiftness (with Yearning Lv. 3) to make it a ~16% engraving.

Similarly, for Entropy builds (extra Crit Damage), KBW efficiency drops a bit. You’re usually picking between it and Cursed Doll, which also loses efficiency when paired with Adrenaline. Having about 82% Crit Rate makes them equal (if you’re running Adrenaline 3), but KBW gains more from crit synergies.

Perfect Suppression Lv.1 vs Lv.3

Similar to our combat engraving situation, Perfect Suppression is a poor scaling engraving. It scales linearly (20 > 28> 36) and only buffs normal skill damage. This means that abilities like Decimate and Rising Claw, which are a considerable part of our damage, are not buffed by it.

1 Spender? 2 Spenders? 3 Spenders?

Simply put, 1 Spender isn’t viable since damage is bad.

Entropy runs 2 spenders since there’s no worthy 3rd spender with the back attack affix. Using any of the other spenders in place of damage skills (like Decimate or Thrust Impact) just means less damage.

Nightmare builds have 3 good spenders (Grind Chain, Spinning Weapon, Cruel Cutter with the backattack-removing tripod) and thus can afford to run it when paired with enough gauge generation.

Rising Claw vs Slasher // Howl vs Demonic Clone

This is more of a personal choice.

Slasher vs Rising Claw

With the new tripods, Slasher has become a utility skill. You can use it for synergy + nimble movement uptime, and with a CD gem it can even be used to upkeep adrenaline all by itself. This is specially handy for crit-heavy builds since they lack move speed for Raid Captain. But it also has the downside of lower gauge generation.

Rising Claw is a better counter (bigger hitbox) and does decent damage, while also generating more gauge than Slasher, but lacks utility. This is usually better suited for Swift-oriented builds since you cover the lack of nimble movement uptime with Swiftness.

Howl vs Demonic Clone vs Grip

Howl provides more gauge generation per cast, and applies synergy. But it lacks paralysis immunity and has a long CD which means failing it is much more punishing.

Demonic Clone has lower gauge generation per cast, but shorter CD than howl which means more gauge per second. It also has Paralysis Immunity through its Naively Honest tripod, which makes it a safer alternative. It requires Lv.10 to reach the Enh. Encroachment Release (gauge generation) tripod, which means that you need to take points off other skills.

Demon’s Grip is a newer alternative thanks to the buff to gauge generation it got. It has better gauge/sec generation than Howl (albeit lower than Demonic Clone), and while it also lacks Paralysis Immunity, it compensates with a faster animation.
